@The_Archer-he2ft Yes, that's why I go to see any Jurassic movie, since Lost World and latter established the pattern. The first film was full of awe and intrigue, and made me feel like a kid again. I DO NOT believe there will be any further iterations that will capture that spirit. 
As for your comment about rehashed dino attack scenes, they're all uniquely fun, even the ones contained in a dumb movie like JPIII. That's what I buy the ticket for since 1997, and I understand if everyone else feels like Charlie Brown-- hoping for Crichton's genius to reappear. The man's long dead, and no one is sadder than me about it. We're left with David Koepp, instead.
If you can't critically distinguish the thrill scenes from one another, you have my pity.

@alexandergurdebeke1214 Movie tickets are sold as a one-time experience for the time slot you booked.
	•	The cinema’s obligation is to screen the movie you paid for — if the film runs as scheduled and the sound/picture is fine, they’ve delivered the service.
	•	Disliking the movie’s content, acting, plot, or vibe is subjective — so cinemas won’t refund for personal taste.

@Sliider36 
Crichton only wanted to write the first book, the second was exclusively for film-adaptation purposes. And hilariously the second film adapts almost nothing from it.
I still think the best post-Lost-World Jurassic Park Media is Trespasser, it's the only sequel in my view. Best lore too.

@insanity4224 
What makes JP1 hold up so well is a perfect blending of Animatronics and CGI, and most of the CGI being used in very specific shots that hide the imperfections.
They knew what they were doing, and did everything very well for 1993.

